    "content": "**Geopolitiks Snacks** — April 11, 2026\n\n---\n\n## 🕊️ Vance Is in Islamabad. Iran Wants Two Things First. The Strait Is Still Closed.\n\nDay 42. Vance, Witkoff, and Kushner arrived in Pakistan for ceasefire negotiations with Iran. The Strait of Hormuz remains effectively closed.\n\n- **Iran's conditions:** Parliamentary speaker Ghalibaf says two things must happen before talks can begin: a ceasefire in Lebanon and the release of Iran's blocked assets. Neither has happened.\n- **The impasse:** The ceasefire technically exists. The Strait \"technically\" agreed to reopen. Iran is charging over $1M per ship. Trump publicly accused Iran of \"doing a very poor job\" honoring the deal.\n\n*Three of the US's most powerful negotiators are in a hotel in Islamabad and the Strait is still running a toll booth. Day 42.*\n\n**Sources:** [Al Jazeera](https://www.aljazeera.com/news/liveblog/2026/4/11/iran-war-live-us-negotiators-due-to-arrive-in-pakistan-for-ceasefire-talks) | [NPR](https://www.npr.org/2026/04/10/g-s1-117013/trump-iran-strait-of-hormuz) | [NBC News](https://www.nbcnews.com/world/iran/live-blog/live-updates-trump-iran-hormuz-israel-lebanon-ceasefire-talks-pakistan-rcna285140)\n\n---\n\n## 💰 Trump Is Now Threatening Tariffs on Countries That Sold Weapons to Iran\n\nWhile thanking China for its role in the ceasefire, Trump announced a potential 50% tariff on any country that supplied weapons to Iran. China supplied weapons to Iran.\n\n- **The contradiction:** Washington is simultaneously thanking Beijing for helping broker peace and threatening to tariff its weapons clients — a group that prominently includes China and Russia.\n- **The math:** The US and China are already at 145%/125% on bilateral tariffs. Adding 50% for Iran arms sales would be mathematically interesting, though the legal mechanism is, per tradition, unclear.\n\n*\"We're grateful for your help with the ceasefire, also you might owe us 50%.\" Diplomatic.*\n\n**Sources:** [South China Morning Post](https://www.scmp.com/news/china/diplomacy/article/3349416/trump-warns-50-cent-tariffs-arms-suppliers-iran)\n\n---\n\n## 🛢️ Iran and China Are Using Hormuz to Attack the Dollar, Not Just the West\n\nThe Hormuz closure is not only a military tactic — it's a financial one. China and Iran are testing alternatives to dollar-denominated oil markets in real time.\n\n- **The mechanism:** With the Strait effectively closed, China has routed payments for Iranian oil through yuan-denominated clearing systems and third-party intermediaries, accelerating a shift already underway.\n- **The calculation:** Iran gets leverage, China gets a live test of dollar-bypass infrastructure. The US inherits a strategic problem that compound interest makes worse every week.\n\n*The Strait of Hormuz is not just an oil choke point anymore. It's also a currency experiment.*\n\n**Sources:** [Al Jazeera Economy](https://www.aljazeera.com/economy/2026/4/8/in-strait-of-hormuz-iran-and-china-take-aim-at-us-dollar-hegemony)\n\n---\n\n## 🤝 The Trump-Xi Summit Already Has a Script: Chips for Rare Earths\n\nThe May summit between Trump and Xi is being shaped by a clear mutual leverage framework: US semiconductor access vs Chinese rare earth supply.\n\n- **The US card:** Advanced semiconductor export controls — China needs sub-14nm chips and equipment to stay competitive in AI and defense.\n- **China's card:** Rare earth export controls — suspended for one year until November 2026, but the window is a negotiating signal, not a truce. Defense supply chains for F-35s, Tomahawk missiles, and submarine components run through Chinese rare earths.\n\n*A summit framed as \"you need our chips, we need your minerals\" is just an arms trade with better PR.*\n\n**Sources:** [CSIS](https://www.csis.org/analysis/chinas-new-rare-earth-and-magnet-restrictions-threaten-us-defense-supply-chains) | [Fortune](https://fortune.com/2026/03/15/scott-bessent-us-china-talks-trump-xi-summit-iran-trade-war-tariffs/) | [Clark Hill](https://www.clarkhill.com/news-events/news/china-hits-pause-on-rare-earth-export-controls-and-what-it-means-for-supply-chains/)"
  }
